## 1. Usage‑Based Pricing Is Now The Default, Not The Edge Case

- Adoption is already mainstream:
  - As of 2026, about **74% of suppliers** delivering software via cloud or embedded deployments are using some form of **usage‑based pricing**, and a majority expect usage‑based revenue to keep growing. [stripe](https://stripe.com/resources/more/usage-based-pricing-strategy-for-saas)
  - Guides now treat usage‑based as a **primary model** alongside per‑seat and hybrid, not an experiment. [nxcode](https://www.nxcode.io/resources/news/saas-pricing-strategy-guide-2026)
- Value metric = your unfair advantage:
  - Stripe emphasizes that the **value metric** you pick (API calls, tokens, tasks, etc.) shapes:
    - Packaging.
    - Pricing page.
    - How buyers interpret their bill.
    - Churn risk when bills arrive. [stripe](https://stripe.com/resources/more/usage-based-pricing-strategy-for-saas)
  - For AI/API businesses, usage metrics like **requests, tokens, data processed, compute time** are explicitly called out as good fits. [zignuts](https://www.zignuts.com/blog/usage-based-pricing-saas)
- Why it matters for Tap919:
  - You are literally building a **usage meter for AI calls**.
  - If you control the meter, you control:
    - Pricing evolution.
    - How easy it is to run experiments.
    - The data everyone else wishes they had.

**Move:** Lock in 2–3 primary value metrics per lane:
- “Requests” for simple models.
- “Tokens” for LLMs.
- “Tasks” for high‑order BlackMind actions.
Then **never** expose vendor‑specific noise; always sell normalized `tap919:` units. [nxcode](https://www.nxcode.io/resources/news/saas-pricing-strategy-guide-2026)

